'''Frans Dhia Jirjis Haddad''' (born 14 July 1993), commonly known as '''Frans Putros''' ({{langx|ar|فرانس بطرس}}; {{langx|syr|ܦܪܢܣ ܦܘܛܪܘܣ}}), is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre-back]], [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Full-back]] or [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]] for [[Super League (Indonesia)|Super League]] club [[Persib Bandung]]. Born in Denmark, he represents the [[Iraq national football team|Iraq national team]].

==Club career==
Putros began his youth career at [[IK Skovbakken]], and was picked up by [[Aarhus Gymnastikforening|AGF]] in 2004, where he played a number of years in the youth and reserve teams for the club. He made his [[Danish Superliga]] debut on 16 November 2012, playing the full 90 minutes in a match against [[FC Nordsjælland]].

In fall 2013, Putros was loaned to [[Silkeborg IF]], where he was reunited with the former AGF assistant coach [[Jesper Sørensen]], who had become the head coach of Silkeborg IF. After a successful stay in Silkeborg, Putros signed a permanent contract at the end of 2013.<ref name="silkeborgif.com">[http://www.silkeborgif.com/nyheder/seneste-nyheder/2013/12/20/frans-dhia-putros-bliver-i-sif/ Frans Dhia Putros stays in SIF (in Danish)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304025611/http://www.silkeborgif.com/nyheder/seneste-nyheder/2013/12/20/frans-dhia-putros-bliver-i-sif/ |date=2016-03-04 }}, News article from Silkeborgif.com, accessed on January 7, 2014.</ref> Putros joined [[FC Fredericia|Fredericia]] in 2015;<ref>[http://www.bold.dk/fodbold/nyheder/fredericia-snupper-putros/ Fredericia snupper Putros], bold.dk, 18 January 2016</ref> he decided to run out his contract at the end of 2017 to sign a two-year deal with Hobro IK.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bold.dk/fodbold/nyheder/hobro-henter-frans-dhia-putros-til-vinter/|title=Hobro henter Frans Dhia Putros til vinter|last=bold.dk|website=bold.dk|date=10 August 2017 |access-date=2017-11-08}}</ref>

Putros joined [[Hobro IK]] in August 2017.<ref>[https://www.bold.dk/fodbold/nyheder/hobro-henter-frans-dhia-putros-til-vinter/ Hobro henter Frans Dhia Putros til vinter]‚ bold.dk, 10 August 2017</ref> He left the club at the end of 2019, where his contract expired. On 11 January 2020, he signed a two-and-a-half-year contract with [[Viborg FF]].<ref>[https://www.vff.dk/nyheder2/frontpagenews/11751-vff-henter-frans-putros VFF henter Frans Putros], vff.dk, 11 January 2020</ref>

==International career==
Putros was born in Denmark and is of [[Assyrian people|Assyrian ethnicity]] from Iraq. Putros made his debut for the [[Iraq national football team|Iraq national team]] in a [[Exhibition game|friendly]] 3–0 win over [[Palestine national football team|Palestine]] on 4 August 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/lineups?gameId=524102|title=Palestine vs. Iraq – Football Match Line-Ups – August 4, 2018 – ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> He was part of the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup]] squad.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.goal.com/en-au/news/afc-asian-cup-2019-all-squads-revealed-final-23-man-lists/ney7a241n52o1j1ga2b9gch3u| title = Every AFC Asian Cup 2019 Squad Revealed – Final 23-man lists |work=Goal.com }}</ref> He was later called up for the [[2023 AFC Asian Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/team/squad/_/id/4375/league/AFC.ASIAN.CUP |title=Iraq Squad – AFC Asian Cup 2023 |publisher=ESPN }}</ref>

